<h2 id="statistical-model">Statistical Model</h2>

<h3 id="two-factor-factorial-model">Two-Factor Factorial Model</h3>

\[Y_{ijk} = \mu + \alpha_i + \beta_j + (\alpha\beta)_{ij} + \varepsilon_{ijk}\]

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>Meaning</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>$\mu$</td>
      <td>Overall mean</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$\alpha_i$</td>
      <td>Main effect of Factor A, level $i$</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$\beta_j$</td>
      <td>Main effect of Factor B, level $j$</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$(\alpha\beta)_{ij}$</td>
      <td>Interaction effect of A and B</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>$\varepsilon_{ijk}$</td>
      <td>Random error, $\varepsilon \sim N(0, \sigma^2)$</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3 id="three-factor-factorial-model">Three-Factor Factorial Model</h3>

\[\begin{aligned}
Y_{ijkl} =\;&amp; \mu + \alpha_i + \beta_j + \gamma_k \\
&amp;+ (\alpha\beta)_{ij} + (\alpha\gamma)_{ik} \\
&amp;+ (\beta\gamma)_{jk} + (\alpha\beta\gamma)_{ijk} \\
&amp;+ \varepsilon_{ijkl}
\end{aligned}\]

<p>The number of effects grows rapidly with $k$:</p>

